title: For Sale:  *LEFT HANDED* Remington m700 in .260 *CUSTOM PACKAGE*
postcontent:
I have a custom, left-hand m700 in .260 that is unfortunately relegated to safe queen status. There is nowhere to shoot around here where I can appreciate the .260's abilities. I had a 300-yard range, and they got shut down. LAME! I live in High Point, NC. 

My rifle began life as a left-handed Remington m700 SPS-Varmint in .308. I removed the barrel and stock and sent the action to Montana Rifleman to re-barreled in .260 and have the action squared and the lugs lapped. I chose a #8 heavy match barrel that tapers from 1.25" to 1" at the muzzle, so one step below a bull barrel. Barrel is 24" with a 1 in 8.5 twist. I added a Badger Recoil lug and MR also removed the factory bluing. 

Next I Duracoated the whole barreled action in Tactical Black. That is their non-reflective black finish. The nice thing about Duracoat is that if you hate the color I chose, you just paint over it and your metal protection factor improves. 

For the stock I went with a Manners T-4 non-adjustable. The stock is fantastic quality and if you run out of ammo, you have a highly effective club to use. Bottom metal is stock Remington with a MagXtender which makes capacity 7 rounds in the box. 

Next I went to the glass aisle and ordered a Falcon Menace 4-14x Front Focal Plane (FFP) tactical scope. It has target turrets and their "ESLR" mil dot reticle. The scope is attached by an EGW one-piece rail and Burris Signature Zee rings (two screw model). I have Butler Creek flip-ups on the scope. 

No trigger work was ever done as none of the custom trigger guys will own up to having a left-hand model. Timney used to, so if you can find one good luck. I think the X-mark is fine in my unscientific opinion, but I'm not a connoisseur. Safety is intact and working. 

I have maybe 130 rounds down the tube, period. Hardly broken in, but shoots well even in my amateur hands. Anyone Interested? 

Will so $1,700 without scope/rings and $2,000 with scope and rings.  Package would include a Hardigg Storm iM3300 case, Dewey rod, Lucas bore guide, brushes/jags, etc., and you can have all of my .260 ammo. Send me an e-mail address for pics/ammo inventory. 

-Chris

title: For Sale:  Star Model B "target" version 9mm  SPF
postcontent:
Sold Pending Funds


Star model B
9mm automatic based upon the 1911, but with a narrower frame and no grip safety.
Adjustable rear sight and full length 5" barrel.
Blued steel.
Military style spur hammer.
Checkered brown plastic grips.
Magazine safety was removed by prior owner.
Original factory 8 rd magazine and cleaning rod.
Comes with an extra firing pin and a Zoom "snap cap".

I really like the design of this pistol, and assumed it would be the perfect gun for me. Paid $375 for this pistol last month, sight unseen, as it had been represented to me as being in "excellent condition with 98% finish." I would call it "very good" condition with maybe 90% finish.

I've heard the Star model B is extremely reliable. This one had 3 stovepipes in 40 rds using Remington FMJ.  This is a Spanish pistol, and it is possible the Remington wasn't loaded hot enough. It may be due to the magazine spring, as each jam was the final round in the mag. Triple K makes a replacement magazine for this pistol which might eliminate this problem. I would also recommend replacing the extractor, just to make sure all bases are covered.  I'm not a gunsmith and I don't have the time or inclination to play with it until it runs 100%.  Pistol is extremely accurate. All rounds made a very tight grouping at 30 ft.

Pistol came with an "extra magazine" . . . but it was for the other Star the seller had (BM) and does not fit . . . but you can sell it to someone who has a BM for $30 or so.

Pistol fires and functions well, but reliability is not up to my standards and I don't want to waste the time and expense experimenting with different magazines, etc. There are two things you need to know about this pistol. First, it should never be fired without a snap cap (provided) or the firing pin may be damaged (extra provided). Also, because it is an antique, high pressure +P ammo should probably be avoided.

I had originally intended to invest in extra magazines and custom grips but I've decided to sell it at a loss instead.

This pistol, in my opinion, is not worth the $375 I paid for it (even though I've never seen adjustable sights on a model B before). I'd estimate its worth to be closer to $250. I'm asking $200 CASH, or I'd be willing to swap for a quantity of decent 9mm ammunition.

title: For Sale/Trade:  7.62x39 Ammo RARE
postcontent:
US 7.62 ammo can full of Plastic Core 7.62x39 East German Ammo.  Really rare and unique.  Excellent home defense ammo as the plastic core negates the over-penetration of FMJ and Hollowpoint ammo.  Used in German CQB situations since it has very low recoil to keep you on target and the previous ball ammo tended to ricochet when it hit cement walls.  Imported into the states a while back as practice ammo for indoor ranges as the plastic core wouldn't destroy the backstop.  Head stamp states 05 79, 05 is East German and 79 is the year of manufacture.  

Will not cycle in SKS's, however works well in AK's.  Any offers considered thanks for looking.

postcontent:
I have tickets for the Lowcountry Friends of the NRA Banquet! Get them now while there still available (and going fast)!

What is it for?

The Friends of the NRA is the grassroots side of the NRA. Half of the money raised goes into a fund that stays right here in South Carolina. It is given away through grants to organizations the help promote the shooting sports with youth, women, and all other shooters. Frequent recipients of grant money include ROTC programs, Shooting clubs, 4H clubs, police departments, and many more.

What is it? 

It is going to be a night filled with fun, games, and a seafood dinner. We've even got a veteran of Iraqi Freedom as our guest speaker. If you've ever been out to the Dorchester Shrine Club you know it's a beautiful place to have just such an event. Come on out for a great time!

We are going to have many guns that we are auctioning off, both live and silent, as well as tons of other prizes all given away at the banquet. Our two featured guns are a Glock 22 (.40 S&W) and a Kimber 84 (.308 Win). Both guns are simply fantastic, I've got special drawing tickets available for both of them. You don't even have to be there to win! We'll call you!

When/Where is it?

The fun starts at 6 PM on Saturday, April 24. The event will be at the Dorchester Shrine Club.

How much is it?

Tickets are $35 for 1 or $60 for a couple, Youth tickets (12 and under) are only $15.

Come on out and lets have a good time supporting a great cause. Give me a call at REDACTED (my name is Andrew), or send me an email at REDACTED and I'll get you hooked up with tickets to the event. Look forward to seeing you out there!

title: For Sale:  Model  1894 Winchester
postcontent:
This is is an early Model 1894 Winchester 30-30 WCF with an antique Pre-1897 serial number in the 148,000 range.  Standard rifle with 26" rectangle barrel, full magazine, and crescent buttplate.  The front sight is a Lyman hunting front...a very good sight that features an ivory tipped blade that's matted across the front to reduce glare. The rear sight is a standard 2 leaf Winchester express sight which would have been standard on an early smokeless powder rifle. The barrel has the early style Winchester address and caliber markings across the top and the Nickel Steel barrel marking in its proper place on the left side just behind the rear sight.  Hammer has the early style checkering with dipped border.  Upper tang has the correct Winchester and Model designations along with Jonathon Browning's August 21, 1894 patent date.   The Model 1894 the first commercially available smokeless powder cartridges in the world.  The caliber was basically intended as a light hunting round for small to medium sized game.      
Overall condition is NRA Antique Excellent 80% original receiver blue and 95% original blue on the barrel and magazine tube.  The loading port still shows 85% bright fire blue.  Hammer shows 85% strong original case colors while the lever has mostly silvered out with 15% colors remaining near the top just below the action.  Very good screws overal. Very Good wood with some light handling marks that's untouched with perfect wood to metal fit.  No chips, cracks, or repairs.  Nice action with a Very Good bore.
Please feel free to call me if you have any questions.  REDACTED

title: For Sale:  Match grade handloads - precision ammuntion
postcontent:
With the rush on the factory ammuntion companies, quality has taken a drastic turn for the worse...I reload only high quality, match grade ammunition.

Custom loads available, loaded to your specifications or mine!
Once fired or new brass is meticulously preped, here's my process for most calibers:
tumble clean, inspect and sort
full length resize and deprime
case trim length and chamfer as required(rifle only)
uniform flash holes (as required)
tumble polish (looks better than factory new!)
flare case mouth (pistol only)
prime with CCI primers (no cheap junk here!)
Charge case with powder (usually done with benchrest powder dispenser = +/- .05 grain)
Seat bullet to precision depth
Factory crimp (MOST sizes)

Pistol bullets are Montana Gold except for .45 acp which are Delta Precision
Rifle bullets are Sierra or Hornady - your spec.
Limited quantities, I handload quality ammunition in small lots, I'm not a commercial reloader just interested in your $
